    <text id="F3532T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>William W. Walker requests leave to attend to the health of his ailing
                father.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
               

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1862-12-20">December 20, 1862</date>
                        <name type="place">Camp near Falmouth <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>To John Stewart, Adjt. 126 <abbr expan="Regiment 
 Pennsylvania">Regt
                        Pa</abbr><lb/> Sir-</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>Having just received a dispatch from home informing me of the dangerous illness
                    of my father, and of his request to see me. I have the honor to ask for a leave
                    of absence of twenty days to proceed to my home: Waynesboro <abbr
                        expan="Pennsylvania">Pa</abbr>. If it would entitle me to further
                    consideration I would urge that for three days past I have been very sick, and
                    am daily growing worse with but little hope of recovery while remaining in Camp.
                    Including myself, my father has five sons, all at this time absent in the
                    service of the United States.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very Respectfully Yours</salute>
                    <signed>W. W. Walker, <abbr expan="Captain Commanding 
 Company">Capt Comm
                        Co.</abbr> E 126 <abbr expan="Regiment 
 Pennsylvania">Regt
                    Pa.</abbr></signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
